data.content:
Here's the output:

```json
{
  "Name": "Alice",
  "Age": 30
}
```

**Key point:** In C#, a positional record `Person(string Name, int Age)` synthesises properties that are already PascalCase. `System.Text.Json` preserves property names by default, so no naming policy is required — you get PascalCase out of the box.

The full `Program.cs`:

```csharp
using System.Text.Json;

var person = new Person("Alice", 30);

var options = new JsonSerializerOptions { WriteIndented = true };
string json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(person, options);

Console.WriteLine(json);

public record Person(string Name, int Age);
```

> Note: I capitalised the record parameters (`Name`, `Age`) to follow C# convention — positional record parameters become public properties, so PascalCase is idiomatic. If you keep them lowercase (`name`, `age`), the generated properties will also be lowercase and the JSON keys will be `name`/`age`.
